WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:28.160
I'm usually the

00:00:28.160 --> 00:00:32.320
shiny-headed guy you see in some people's photos, like when they take photos with Hadley

00:00:32.320 --> 00:00:36.200
and you see there's a bald, shiny-headed guy next to him, that's usually me, and they're

00:00:36.200 --> 00:00:39.799
like, why does this guy keep showing up in these photos?

00:00:39.799 --> 00:00:44.240
If you attended my talk last year at rstudio Conf, you know that I am regrettably not a

00:00:44.240 --> 00:00:47.320
data scientist, contrary to what Hadley said, yet.

00:00:47.320 --> 00:00:48.880
One of these days I will get there.

00:00:48.880 --> 00:00:56.799
I do enjoy playing with R. I find it, my background is in software engineering and mathematics,

00:00:56.799 --> 00:01:00.200
but I love to play with R and I love to explore how you can use it to understand the world

00:01:00.200 --> 00:01:04.919
more deeply, and hopefully make better data-driven decisions.

00:01:04.919 --> 00:01:10.639
It is precisely the question of understanding the world and making better data-driven decisions.

00:01:10.639 --> 00:01:13.400
This is going to be so easy for me, I can tell.

00:01:13.400 --> 00:01:19.720
You know, it's funny, I was talking to my wife and my seven-year-old said, you know,

00:01:19.720 --> 00:01:22.000
would dad get fired if he screws up on this presentation?

00:01:22.000 --> 00:01:27.040
I said, I don't think I will be fired for this, but all right.

00:01:27.040 --> 00:01:33.800
So six years ago I got into R and eventually I met JJ, and at the time I didn't fully understand

00:01:33.800 --> 00:01:38.519
or appreciate just how incredible the R community was, and continues to be, and the positive

00:01:38.519 --> 00:01:40.760
impact you all have on this world.

00:01:40.760 --> 00:01:46.519
I also hadn't gotten a full picture of what was possible with this remarkable tool chain.

00:01:46.519 --> 00:01:49.760
You'll hear a lot from speakers this week about the power of the open-source packages

00:01:49.760 --> 00:01:53.400
that are created in R, and I don't need to tell you guys about all the incredible things

00:01:53.400 --> 00:01:55.720
that are sort of coming down the pipe.

00:01:55.720 --> 00:02:00.239
My goal in this talk is to give you a deeper look at our studio story, what we believe

00:02:00.239 --> 00:02:07.559
in, and how organizations have adopted R and the R ecosystem to solve real-world problems.

00:02:07.559 --> 00:02:11.639
So given the rate of innovation and change, it is often difficult to stay on top of what

00:02:11.639 --> 00:02:14.360
is possible and how the puzzle pieces fit together.

00:02:14.360 --> 00:02:18.199
I happen to know this because last year I was lucky enough to visit 30 different customers

00:02:18.199 --> 00:02:20.440
all over the world.

00:02:20.440 --> 00:02:23.880
And my goal was to sort of talk to them about the new products we're building, where we're

00:02:23.880 --> 00:02:27.059
going, and to see whether the problems that we're solving are the same problems that they

00:02:27.059 --> 00:02:29.800
are trying to solve for themselves.

00:02:29.800 --> 00:02:33.960
And it became really obvious that most people don't have the full story, and it's really

00:02:33.960 --> 00:02:34.960
hard.

00:02:34.960 --> 00:02:37.919
And it occurred to me that the reason for that is because we've never told that story

00:02:37.919 --> 00:02:38.919
publicly.

00:02:38.919 --> 00:02:45.320
So let's make sure that you guys walk out of here with three things today.

00:02:45.320 --> 00:02:46.880
What is the way of RStudio?

00:02:46.880 --> 00:02:47.880
What do we believe in?

00:02:48.559 --> 00:02:50.160
Why do we do the work that we do?

00:02:50.160 --> 00:02:53.160
How can you adopt R in production?

00:02:53.160 --> 00:02:55.520
And finally, how does R sustain itself?

00:02:55.520 --> 00:03:00.279
You'd be surprised how many people still ask me that question.

00:03:00.279 --> 00:03:02.440
To answer that, I'm going to take you back to 1439.

00:03:02.440 --> 00:03:07.279
Does anybody know what was created in 1439, what was invented?

00:03:07.279 --> 00:03:08.279
The printing press.

00:03:08.279 --> 00:03:11.520
I knew somebody in the audience would know the answer to that question, so it wasn't

00:03:11.520 --> 00:03:12.520
so hard.

00:03:12.520 --> 00:03:17.080
At about that time, there was a goldsmith by the name of Johannes Gutenberg, and he

00:03:17.080 --> 00:03:20.320
invented the movable type-based printing press.

00:03:20.320 --> 00:03:26.199
Prior to its arrival, the process for creating content was one where people would write manuscripts,

00:03:26.199 --> 00:03:30.679
usually monks, because they were the only ones that could read and write, and the process

00:03:30.679 --> 00:03:36.759
was really, really slow and very expensive, which meant that knowledge got centralized

00:03:36.759 --> 00:03:41.720
into the hands of the few, and being able to validate the authenticity and correctness

00:03:41.720 --> 00:03:44.600
of the work was really, really difficult.

00:03:44.600 --> 00:03:48.160
Developing a press that could accelerate the creation of perfect fidelity copies of

00:03:48.160 --> 00:03:53.399
a book, most notably the Good Book at the time, radically changed who could have access

00:03:53.399 --> 00:03:59.179
to knowledge and increased the confidence that everybody was seeing the same information.

00:03:59.179 --> 00:04:05.279
Many believe, and including Wikipedia, that the arrival of the printing press helped start

00:04:05.279 --> 00:04:08.759
and fuel the scientific revolution in the 16th century.

00:04:08.759 --> 00:04:14.160
I'm particularly attracted to the few concepts in here about ushering in the era of mass

00:04:14.160 --> 00:04:18.760
communication, permanently altering the structure of society.

00:04:18.760 --> 00:04:25.200
Now 500 years later, we have the prime directive.

00:04:25.200 --> 00:04:29.160
John Chambers wrote about this in his book, and I think it's so important and it captures

00:04:29.160 --> 00:04:33.239
who we are and what we do so well that it bears reading out loud.

00:04:33.239 --> 00:04:38.959
Science, business, and many other areas of society continually rely on understanding

00:04:38.959 --> 00:04:45.600
data, and that understanding frequently involves large and complicated data processes.

00:04:45.600 --> 00:04:49.880
Those who receive the results of modern data analysis have limited opportunity to verify

00:04:49.880 --> 00:04:53.519
the results by direct observation.

00:04:53.519 --> 00:04:59.320
Users of the analysis have no option but to trust the analysis and by extension the software

00:04:59.320 --> 00:05:01.200
that produced it.

00:05:01.200 --> 00:05:06.640
This places an obligation on all creators of software to program in such a way that

00:05:06.640 --> 00:05:10.160
the computations can be understood and trusted.

00:05:10.160 --> 00:05:14.000
This obligation I label the prime directive.

00:05:14.000 --> 00:05:18.160
So for us, code is reproducibility.

00:05:18.160 --> 00:05:19.839
Reproducibility is good science.

00:05:19.839 --> 00:05:24.279
If you believe in code and reproducibility, you can get reuse, you can get automation,

00:05:24.279 --> 00:05:26.839
you can get scheduling, you can get parameterization.

00:05:26.839 --> 00:05:29.980
Good science for us is good business.

00:05:29.980 --> 00:05:33.799
So I don't want to rush over this too quickly.

00:05:34.640 --> 00:05:38.880
If you can reproduce your analysis, you can recreate it, you can repeat it, and in the

00:05:38.880 --> 00:05:44.399
same context or a new one, and you can always reproduce your analysis if you record your

00:05:44.399 --> 00:05:47.440
analysis in code.

00:05:47.440 --> 00:05:52.920
So last November, I was at a conference in Barcelona, the Gartner conference, and there

00:05:52.920 --> 00:05:55.799
was this big movement that was starting up called the no code movement.

00:05:55.799 --> 00:05:58.239
I don't know how many of you guys are familiar with it.

00:05:58.239 --> 00:06:02.440
But I sat there and I listened to what folks were saying and I saw the CIOs sort of like

00:06:02.440 --> 00:06:04.959
oh, this is really exciting, this is going to be the new world, I don't have to hire

00:06:04.959 --> 00:06:09.480
data scientists, I don't have to code, you know, and it occurred to me that we are basically

00:06:09.480 --> 00:06:10.480
the opposite.

00:06:10.480 --> 00:06:16.359
I'm like, why did I show up to this show?

00:06:16.359 --> 00:06:21.600
So I figured it would be good to just remind people of what we believe.

00:06:21.600 --> 00:06:25.600
There are four things, four reasons that we love code, right?

00:06:25.600 --> 00:06:30.040
The repeatability I suspect everybody here would agree with, right?

00:06:30.040 --> 00:06:33.959
It's important for your analysis to be repeatable and reproducible down the road.

00:06:33.959 --> 00:06:37.799
It's one of the key tenants, if you will, of the scientific process.

00:06:37.799 --> 00:06:40.959
But there are other elements that are also important.

00:06:40.959 --> 00:06:42.399
Inspectable analysis.

00:06:42.399 --> 00:06:46.720
So inspectable analysis speaks to the ability to review the work, point out flaws in the

00:06:46.720 --> 00:06:49.000
assumptions or suggest improvements.

00:06:49.000 --> 00:06:54.959
It ultimately helps one understand how the results were achieved in a transparent manner.

00:06:54.959 --> 00:07:00.880
Diffable analysis addresses the ability to leverage that same work again for future work.

00:07:00.880 --> 00:07:03.679
Or to build on or extend it.

00:07:03.679 --> 00:07:07.359
If you want to solve something new, you might Google for it and understand that someone

00:07:07.359 --> 00:07:11.160
has done what someone has done to solve the same or similar problem.

00:07:11.160 --> 00:07:14.679
It serves as a foundation for sharing.

00:07:14.679 --> 00:07:16.040
And then finally diffable analysis.

00:07:16.040 --> 00:07:19.200
I tried this out a few for a couple of days and most people are like, I don't know what

00:07:19.200 --> 00:07:21.839
diffable analysis is.

00:07:21.839 --> 00:07:25.440
This may seem like a variant of inspectability.

00:07:25.440 --> 00:07:27.880
But it's important in its own right.

00:07:27.880 --> 00:07:31.839
What we're talking about with diffable analysis is you being able to compare the changes made

00:07:31.839 --> 00:07:35.399
to your analysis over time or somebody else's analysis over time.

00:07:35.399 --> 00:07:38.720
It makes it easier for you to understand why decisions were made and if there were mistakes,

00:07:38.720 --> 00:07:41.760
where the errors were introduced along the way.

00:07:41.760 --> 00:07:46.720
So for us, ultimately we believe complex problems will require code.

00:07:46.720 --> 00:07:48.559
Code is communication.

00:07:48.559 --> 00:07:49.559
Communication is critical.

00:07:49.640 --> 00:07:53.320
What gives you then leverage?

00:07:53.320 --> 00:07:56.480
Single data scientist creates something that a whole bunch of other people in the organization

00:07:56.480 --> 00:07:59.059
can use to solve real problems.

00:07:59.059 --> 00:08:02.779
With code, you can inspect how a problem is solved and either adopt it or figure out how

00:08:02.779 --> 00:08:04.320
to improve it yourself.

00:08:04.320 --> 00:08:08.200
And finally, with code, the answer is always yes.

00:08:08.200 --> 00:08:10.679
All right?

00:08:10.679 --> 00:08:14.399
So oh, shoot.

00:08:14.399 --> 00:08:16.399
This is not my last presentation.

00:08:16.399 --> 00:08:17.640
It's too bad.

00:08:17.640 --> 00:08:23.160
I spent all this time getting this nice little animation in place that shows you guys all

00:08:23.160 --> 00:08:24.160
the various packages.

00:08:24.160 --> 00:08:25.839
So this is the final result.

00:08:25.839 --> 00:08:32.440
174 packages that we maintain and support for the R community.

00:08:32.440 --> 00:08:39.599
And we're excited that over 50% of our engineering team works on free and open source software.

00:08:39.599 --> 00:08:43.760
And our company is more than 50% engineering.

00:08:43.760 --> 00:08:49.080
So just because you have really fantastic open source tools doesn't mean that you can

00:08:49.080 --> 00:08:53.200
get them into your production environments or you can get your company to adopt them.

00:08:53.200 --> 00:08:56.760
It turns out that there are multiple constituencies that you have to deal with.

00:08:56.760 --> 00:08:59.359
So data scientist is one of them.

00:08:59.359 --> 00:09:02.440
Business users are another.

00:09:02.440 --> 00:09:07.020
And IT admins or your DevOps or your data engineers, there's a whole class of folks

00:09:07.020 --> 00:09:11.799
that have vested interest in how you operate and how you use your data in production.

00:09:12.320 --> 00:09:15.880
So everybody has a set of they have their own set of activities and they have their

00:09:15.880 --> 00:09:18.840
own set of concerns that they need to worry about.

00:09:18.840 --> 00:09:23.119
So what we've been trying to do is figure out how to make that easier, how to get that

00:09:23.119 --> 00:09:24.960
adoption to happen into the organization.

00:09:24.960 --> 00:09:29.640
How do you get people to move from a world where they have a lot of point and click,

00:09:29.640 --> 00:09:33.700
drag and drop solutions to one that's sort of grounded in code.

00:09:33.700 --> 00:09:37.239
And to that, what we've done is added our commercial products.

00:09:37.239 --> 00:09:38.239
Right?

00:09:38.760 --> 00:09:42.559
And if you take a look, our commercial products are meant to address all of those concerns

00:09:42.559 --> 00:09:45.320
on the right-hand side.

00:09:45.320 --> 00:09:50.280
So I mentioned that I'm going to show you some of the things that we talked about with

00:09:50.280 --> 00:09:52.359
customers over the last year.

00:09:52.359 --> 00:09:56.400
And I'm going to introduce, I'm going to go back to sort of the IDE.

00:09:56.400 --> 00:10:01.640
And if you guys can go back in time and think six, seven years ago, most people were using

00:10:01.640 --> 00:10:03.760
the IDE on a desktop.

00:10:03.760 --> 00:10:07.960
Some organizations started using our studio server to help centralize the workloads and

00:10:08.159 --> 00:10:11.200
better manage capacity and access to the data.

00:10:11.200 --> 00:10:15.239
About six years ago, we started hearing feedback from the IT teams within organizations, and

00:10:15.239 --> 00:10:19.520
they were being asked to help support the growing use of R in their organization.

00:10:19.520 --> 00:10:27.479
They asked for features around, so they wanted to be able to better control access to resources,

00:10:27.479 --> 00:10:31.559
they wanted to be able to audit the usage, they wanted high availability, they wanted

00:10:31.559 --> 00:10:35.599
multiple versions of R, they wanted the ability to start multiple sessions, collaborative

00:10:35.599 --> 00:10:37.320
editing, et cetera.

00:10:37.359 --> 00:10:43.320
So we added all these capabilities into our premium product line, and that actually has

00:10:43.320 --> 00:10:47.039
helped us get over 1,000 enterprise customers today.

00:10:47.039 --> 00:10:52.840
In the past two years, we've seen IT organizations experiment with the use of Docker, and some

00:10:52.840 --> 00:10:55.799
have even started playing with distributed computing platforms.

00:10:55.799 --> 00:11:00.080
The pattern they use is to bake our studio server and Shiny server directly within a

00:11:00.080 --> 00:11:04.880
Docker container so that each session would run a full server process.

00:11:04.880 --> 00:11:09.599
We've been working on a refactoring of professional products to change the execution model, which

00:11:09.599 --> 00:11:12.039
we are calling the launcher.

00:11:12.039 --> 00:11:16.840
In this new model, we have separated the execution of the R process from the server that is responding

00:11:16.840 --> 00:11:18.159
to the user.

00:11:18.159 --> 00:11:21.239
This will allow customers to start an R process on a remote machine.

00:11:21.239 --> 00:11:24.719
So let's actually take a look and see what this looks like.

00:11:24.719 --> 00:11:27.559
Oh, shoot, I forgot.

00:11:27.559 --> 00:11:30.479
Oh, so that's weird that I got that.

00:11:30.520 --> 00:11:35.960
The heart of all of our work is our R packages, right?

00:11:35.960 --> 00:11:43.080
So again, for us, everything starts from the R, the open source, and expands up.

00:11:43.080 --> 00:11:44.520
So let's start with the IDE.

00:11:44.520 --> 00:11:49.520
I'm going to start a new session, and in this session, it happens to be using Kubernetes.

00:11:49.520 --> 00:11:50.760
I'll name the session.

00:11:50.760 --> 00:11:55.799
I'll be able to control the CPU, resources that are used, the memory that is used, and

00:11:55.799 --> 00:11:59.679
the base image that I'm leveraging.

00:11:59.679 --> 00:12:07.760
And once I start the session, I should get an IDE that looks identical to what you guys

00:12:07.760 --> 00:12:14.919
see on your desktops today.

00:12:14.919 --> 00:12:19.559
Not all that impressive, but if you run the plot, I should be able to see the work, and

00:12:19.559 --> 00:12:25.119
now I can go to the Kubernetes dashboard and take a look and see the jobs that are running.

00:12:25.119 --> 00:12:30.679
This is an R process that's running inside of a Docker container on Kubernetes, and you

00:12:30.679 --> 00:12:34.960
can see that it has the same metadata that I entered in the previous report.

00:12:34.960 --> 00:12:41.080
Now going back to the IDE, I can go ahead and take a look, and oh, sorry, this session

00:12:41.080 --> 00:12:46.919
has started with that user's context in the right, with the right level of permissions.

00:12:46.919 --> 00:12:50.359
So if I go back to the packages, I can go ahead and take a look and see this particular

00:12:50.359 --> 00:12:55.479
base image does not have all of the, it has a very limited set of packages, and if I search

00:12:55.479 --> 00:12:59.760
for Shiny, you'll notice that Shiny's not in there.

00:12:59.760 --> 00:13:04.599
If I want to go ahead and start a new session, this time maybe a validated environment, so

00:13:04.599 --> 00:13:09.280
the organization says, okay, there's a set of packages that I'm okay with you guys using.

00:13:09.280 --> 00:13:11.119
They're preconfigured.

00:13:11.119 --> 00:13:18.239
They can bake that into another base image that has those particular packages in them.

00:13:18.239 --> 00:13:31.479
I go ahead and start that project, and here if I search for Shiny, you'll see that the

00:13:31.479 --> 00:13:32.760
Shiny package is there.

00:13:32.760 --> 00:13:37.039
Now this comes from a package manager, the new product that we introduced in October

00:13:37.039 --> 00:13:41.280
called the RStudio Package Manager, and the RStudio Package Manager was created to help

00:13:41.280 --> 00:13:46.359
the IT team be able to manage what versions of packages you have in production, right?

00:13:46.359 --> 00:13:49.359
So you can create different repos.

00:13:49.359 --> 00:13:54.000
Each of these repos can have a subset of packages that have been approved by somebody if you

00:13:54.000 --> 00:14:01.159
want them to, and then any R process that is pointing to that particular repo will be

00:14:01.159 --> 00:14:06.599
able to get exactly the same versions of the R package, so this is speaking again to getting

00:14:06.599 --> 00:14:10.320
a reproducible version of the R code that you're using.

00:14:10.320 --> 00:14:19.479
So the RStudio Package Manager was started in these IT organizations because one of the

00:14:19.479 --> 00:14:27.760
key problems that we've seen is that there's a big spectrum of usage of R in these organizations,

00:14:27.760 --> 00:14:29.479
so some people have a Wild West model.

00:14:29.479 --> 00:14:35.000
You can use any package that you want anywhere, and obviously there's a concern here about

00:14:35.000 --> 00:14:39.200
reproducibility, right, unless you're using something like PackRat.

00:14:39.200 --> 00:14:43.559
Packers lock down their R packages so that you can only use what has been pre-approved

00:14:43.559 --> 00:14:47.400
and blessed, and that's sort of a very draconian process you have to get special approvals

00:14:47.400 --> 00:14:49.320
to get through.

00:14:49.320 --> 00:14:52.500
What we've done with RStudio Package Manager is made it easier for you to be able to cater

00:14:52.500 --> 00:14:57.760
to either end of the spectrum, so on one side of the spectrum, you may say I want my R&D

00:14:57.760 --> 00:15:00.840
team to be able to have access to the latest and greatest version of anything, you know,

00:15:00.840 --> 00:15:05.320
on Crayon or any of our internal packages, but on the other side, you could say, you

00:15:05.320 --> 00:15:10.039
know what, when we get closer to production environments or if we want to go to a validated

00:15:10.039 --> 00:15:16.479
environment, this is a pre-selected set of work that, set of packages that you can use

00:15:16.479 --> 00:15:21.640
and define, and so that hopefully will make it radically easier for organizations to be

00:15:21.640 --> 00:15:23.359
able to manage this.

00:15:23.359 --> 00:15:27.119
So one of the things that you will notice that we've invested quite a bit of time in

00:15:27.119 --> 00:15:32.679
is trying to solve the problem for IT organizations who honestly don't know anything about R,

00:15:32.679 --> 00:15:33.679
right?

00:15:33.679 --> 00:15:35.000
They have a lot of demands.

00:15:35.000 --> 00:15:37.719
There's a lot of new technology that they have to work with, and we want to make it

00:15:37.719 --> 00:15:42.520
much easier for them to use R in production.

00:15:42.520 --> 00:15:45.840
So enough about package management.

00:15:45.840 --> 00:15:51.239
Let's switch to something that everybody here is more comfortable with, Shiny.

00:15:51.239 --> 00:15:55.919
Here's a Shiny application that happens to show you a stock portfolio over time, and

00:15:55.919 --> 00:16:01.159
as you can see, this stock portfolio is indicating that the market's not doing so well.

00:16:01.159 --> 00:16:04.440
Hopefully most of you guys have noticed that.

00:16:04.440 --> 00:16:08.840
But what's powerful about Shiny is that you can give people the ability to interact and

00:16:08.840 --> 00:16:11.479
explore questions and get the answers for themselves.

00:16:11.479 --> 00:16:17.919
So for the sake of the example, let's say I'm showing up in a meeting and I have a bunch

00:16:17.919 --> 00:16:18.919
of stakeholders.

00:16:18.919 --> 00:16:22.239
I pull up this application and we see something that is interesting to us, right?

00:16:22.239 --> 00:16:25.440
And people say, oh, that looks fantastic.

00:16:25.440 --> 00:16:31.320
How do I get this particular report, how do I get a report of this on a weekly basis,

00:16:31.320 --> 00:16:32.320
right?

00:16:32.320 --> 00:16:36.840
And again, what's nice here is that this Shiny application has all the code that it took

00:16:36.840 --> 00:16:39.840
to run it, and so in theory, it's completely reproducible.

00:16:39.840 --> 00:16:43.119
I can hand it to somebody else, and when they run it, they are running exactly the same

00:16:43.119 --> 00:16:46.039
code that you created.

00:16:46.039 --> 00:16:50.960
But so they say, okay, I want this on a weekly basis, or somebody else, some other stakeholder

00:16:50.960 --> 00:16:51.960
says, you know, that's nice.

00:16:51.960 --> 00:16:56.000
I want a slightly different set of variables, but I want that on a monthly basis or a quarterly

00:16:56.000 --> 00:16:57.000
basis.

00:16:57.000 --> 00:16:58.000
So what do you do when that happens?

00:16:58.000 --> 00:17:03.320
And so what we're proposing is that you take a look at R Markdown.

00:17:03.320 --> 00:17:07.880
And R Markdown, so here's an R Markdown doc that has the same logic and visualizations

00:17:07.880 --> 00:17:09.680
that you saw in the Shiny application.

00:17:09.680 --> 00:17:14.359
But an R Markdown, if you haven't seen it, is a text-based literate programming content

00:17:14.359 --> 00:17:19.199
format that allows you to mix prose, code, and output into a single document.

00:17:19.199 --> 00:17:21.959
You can even use LaTeX equations.

00:17:21.959 --> 00:17:28.380
So similar to notebooks, you can have the outputs inline, but one of the key powers

00:17:28.380 --> 00:17:33.119
is that you can reproducibly knit the document into a variety of output formats.

00:17:33.119 --> 00:17:38.160
For those of you who heard my talk last year, you know that I use R Markdown with IOSlides

00:17:38.160 --> 00:17:40.839
to create our quarterly board deck.

00:17:40.839 --> 00:17:43.099
In this example, we'll use PDF.

00:17:43.099 --> 00:17:47.439
So if you take a look at this, this is exactly the same set of visualizations and data that

00:17:47.439 --> 00:17:50.920
we saw in the Shiny application.

00:17:50.920 --> 00:17:55.640
Once I'm happy with this, I can decide to go ahead and save it, save my work.

00:17:55.640 --> 00:17:56.640
And how do I save it?

00:17:56.640 --> 00:17:59.959
I'm going to go ahead and check it in.

00:17:59.959 --> 00:18:03.959
When we go to check it in, this is when we talk about the diffable story.

00:18:03.959 --> 00:18:05.800
This is what we're talking about, right?

00:18:05.800 --> 00:18:11.400
I can actually go ahead and see the exact changes that were introduced.

00:18:11.400 --> 00:18:16.239
And this gives me the ultimate transparency in how much...

00:18:16.239 --> 00:18:18.000
This is so easy.

00:18:18.000 --> 00:18:21.479
The transparency is making it much easier for me to review the spreadsheet than any

00:18:21.479 --> 00:18:24.839
spreadsheet or any point and click solution.

00:18:24.839 --> 00:18:30.280
Once I have what I want, once I've done with it, I go ahead and publish this and share

00:18:30.280 --> 00:18:31.280
it with other people.

00:18:31.280 --> 00:18:34.319
And what I'm proposing here is that you publish it to Connect, because Connect is actually

00:18:34.319 --> 00:18:39.040
the easiest way for you to publish your data products to your organization.

00:18:39.040 --> 00:18:44.680
Connect will actually go ahead and detect all the dependencies and push up the full

00:18:44.680 --> 00:18:47.199
code up to the server.

00:18:47.199 --> 00:18:49.280
So you can go ahead and...

00:18:49.280 --> 00:18:56.880
And the server now can go ahead and recreate that analysis in a secure sandboxed environment.

00:18:56.880 --> 00:19:01.599
Same PDF report that we were looking at earlier.

00:19:01.599 --> 00:19:05.160
Now what's nice about Connect is because all the data is up there, I can go ahead and rerun

00:19:05.160 --> 00:19:07.560
that analysis at any moment in time.

00:19:07.560 --> 00:19:11.839
I can also control who has access to this analysis, right?

00:19:11.839 --> 00:19:12.839
I can say...

00:19:12.839 --> 00:19:13.839
Okay.

00:19:14.000 --> 00:19:15.000
I can see it.

00:19:15.000 --> 00:19:16.000
Only some people can see it.

00:19:16.000 --> 00:19:18.319
I can also email the report out.

00:19:18.319 --> 00:19:25.359
And this particular report allows you, through code, to customize the subject line, the body

00:19:25.359 --> 00:19:31.880
of the email, including the various graphs that we had, and the attachments that are

00:19:31.880 --> 00:19:32.880
included.

00:19:32.880 --> 00:19:38.319
So the attachments here are not only the PDF doc that we looked at earlier, but actually

00:19:38.319 --> 00:19:43.119
any content that you created programmatically in the R Markdown doc.

00:19:43.119 --> 00:19:50.079
So in this case, we have both a CSV file and we have the PowerPoint presentation that

00:19:50.079 --> 00:19:53.479
you may decide, if you look at it and say, okay, this is really great, I'm gonna go ahead

00:19:53.479 --> 00:19:56.719
and send that to my boss, right?

00:19:56.719 --> 00:19:57.719
To my exec.

00:19:57.719 --> 00:20:03.599
The other elements that I did not get a chance to show you here is with R Markdown, with

00:20:03.599 --> 00:20:08.040
the fact that we just did this with R Markdown, you have complete reproducibility of the work

00:20:08.040 --> 00:20:09.040
that you've done.

00:20:09.040 --> 00:20:12.640
One of the other elements we have not shown you is sort of the parameterization of R Markdown

00:20:13.160 --> 00:20:19.000
So you can take that same report that I showed you earlier and expose the same kind of input

00:20:19.000 --> 00:20:23.920
parameters that you saw in Shiny, but then allow the users to go ahead and interact with

00:20:23.920 --> 00:20:24.920
them.

00:20:24.920 --> 00:20:29.599
And for each of these parameterized versions, you can go ahead and send that out to your

00:20:29.599 --> 00:20:30.599
constituency.

00:20:30.599 --> 00:20:34.280
So your constituency can look at it and say, okay, I really like the aggressive version

00:20:34.280 --> 00:20:38.000
of the portfolio, and so I wanna be able to receive that on a weekly basis, because that

00:20:38.000 --> 00:20:39.800
really matters to me.

00:20:40.800 --> 00:20:45.280
For other members of the organization to say, I wanna get this on a quarterly basis, I don't

00:20:45.280 --> 00:20:49.400
care, I have a longer term view in terms of how I think about portfolios, and so I will

00:20:49.400 --> 00:20:51.160
go ahead and pull that in.

00:20:51.160 --> 00:20:55.319
So this is one of the key tenants that we see.

00:20:55.319 --> 00:21:00.439
If you thought about the printing press, this is a way for you to sort of recreate the printing,

00:21:00.439 --> 00:21:03.079
but all through code.

00:21:03.079 --> 00:21:08.599
Next thing that we talk a lot about is that Connect, RStudio Server Pro, and Package Manager

00:21:09.079 --> 00:21:13.040
make it easier for you to put R into production.

00:21:13.040 --> 00:21:16.640
Now most organizations, they don't have just R users, right?

00:21:16.640 --> 00:21:21.359
They have a variety of tools and services and connections that they need to interoperate

00:21:21.359 --> 00:21:22.359
with.

00:21:22.359 --> 00:21:28.119
And so the next thing I wanna spend time on is showing you the next superpower of R, R

00:21:28.119 --> 00:21:29.359
as a glue language, right?

00:21:29.359 --> 00:21:31.500
Many of you guys may have experienced that firsthand.

00:21:31.500 --> 00:21:37.599
So we'll start by showing how you can connect R to Spark, since Spark is still the new hotness,

00:21:37.599 --> 00:21:43.319
I think, and in the IDE, this is available in the open source version, you can connect

00:21:43.319 --> 00:21:48.479
to a Spark cluster, and for those of you who have never seen this, I can create a notebook

00:21:48.479 --> 00:21:55.079
from it, pull it back into the R Markdown doc, and now I can start writing dplyr code

00:21:55.079 --> 00:21:58.000
that I'm familiar with, and what's really powerful about this is that even though I'm

00:21:58.000 --> 00:22:05.560
writing what looks like regular dplyr code that runs in R, when this code looks to run,

00:22:05.560 --> 00:22:10.359
it's actually running in Spark, and so let's take a look and see what that looks like.

00:22:10.359 --> 00:22:14.119
Here's the Spark SQL that this would actually run at that moment in time, and if I go ahead

00:22:14.119 --> 00:22:18.760
and change that code, I can go ahead and run it so that I can get the data back, I can

00:22:18.760 --> 00:22:20.040
get the summary data back.

00:22:20.040 --> 00:22:27.359
So this could be working on a dataset that is very, very large, and similarly, I can

00:22:27.359 --> 00:22:29.839
leverage any of the machine learning algorithms that are in Spark.

00:22:29.839 --> 00:22:32.800
Again, this is leveraging the Sparkly R open source package, you guys can play with it

00:22:32.800 --> 00:22:34.359
if you're interested.

00:22:34.359 --> 00:22:40.880
The next thing that we've sort of invested more time in is on connecting to databases,

00:22:40.880 --> 00:22:44.479
so some of you guys may have seen this, you can connect through the ODBC driver in the

00:22:44.479 --> 00:22:49.719
connections pane, you can explore the schema of a SQL server database in this particular

00:22:49.719 --> 00:22:51.000
case.

00:22:51.000 --> 00:22:58.959
What's new in 1.2 is that you can take that work and pull those, you can sort of edit

00:22:58.959 --> 00:23:03.599
the SQL and manage it and run it locally, and then once you're happy with it, you can

00:23:03.839 --> 00:23:06.680
extract that and pull that into R Markdown.

00:23:06.680 --> 00:23:13.160
Now most people haven't seen what, don't know that R Markdown can include different kinds

00:23:13.160 --> 00:23:21.719
of code chunks, and so this is, we've shown you sort of R, you're now seeing SQL, but

00:23:21.719 --> 00:23:27.880
now we can also, we've added more support for Python in the IDE, so you've always been

00:23:27.880 --> 00:23:32.959
able to add, have Python code, but now you can sort of have the output of the plots come

00:23:32.959 --> 00:23:43.000
in in line just as it would with R, and we've improved the cross chunk data pass through.

00:23:43.000 --> 00:23:49.319
So another language we added support for is D3, through the R2D3 package, so now if you're

00:23:49.319 --> 00:23:54.199
really into D3, it's much easier for you to create these types of JavaScript visualizations

00:23:54.199 --> 00:23:55.839
and include them.

00:23:55.839 --> 00:24:00.520
Finally, those of you, some of you may know about Plumber, which is an open source package

00:24:00.520 --> 00:24:07.319
that you can use to expose REST-based API end points from your code, and in this particular

00:24:07.319 --> 00:24:13.400
case we have a sentiment analysis tool that is exposed through this annotation for the

00:24:13.400 --> 00:24:18.199
predict function, and in the 1.2 release of the IDE, it's easier for you to run those

00:24:18.199 --> 00:24:23.479
APIs locally, test them out, make sure that they're working the way you expect them to,

00:24:23.479 --> 00:24:26.560
and then once you're happy with that, you can go ahead and publish it to connect, just

00:24:26.560 --> 00:24:29.880
as you published the R markdown doc that I showed you earlier, or you can publish the

00:24:29.880 --> 00:24:30.880
Shiny applications.

00:24:30.880 --> 00:24:36.359
And again, we detect all the dependencies, and those of you who may not have caught that,

00:24:36.359 --> 00:24:40.660
but this code is actually using Python, so not only are we detecting the R dependencies,

00:24:40.660 --> 00:24:44.959
we're also detecting the Python dependencies, and we're going to send those up to connect,

00:24:44.959 --> 00:24:50.599
and on connect, you'll be able to sort of now, it's recreating that in that sandbox environment,

00:24:50.599 --> 00:24:52.479
and I can go ahead and try and play with it if I want.

00:24:52.479 --> 00:24:55.859
So again, this is a real model, so let's try out some things.

00:24:55.859 --> 00:25:05.699
If we type in debugging, we'll see what it comes back with as a result, and not entirely

00:25:05.699 --> 00:25:10.900
surprisingly, it came in a 0.149, which is not a particularly high score.

00:25:10.900 --> 00:25:15.420
Now if we go up here, you know, we're in Austin, some people will get a chance to do this,

00:25:15.420 --> 00:25:26.540
you type in great beer, we'll come back and see a 0.88 score, which is much, much better.

00:25:26.540 --> 00:25:31.979
Finally, let's just for yucks and giggles, type in R users.

00:25:31.979 --> 00:25:35.060
Amazingly enough, it comes in at 0.90.

00:25:35.060 --> 00:25:36.819
I swear to you, we did not play with the model.

00:25:36.819 --> 00:25:41.300
This is really what it comes back with for the Python-based sentiment analysis model.

00:25:41.459 --> 00:25:49.020
All right, so just to recap, our studio's goal is to create an organization that can

00:25:49.020 --> 00:25:53.219
have a durable contribution in this world by creating very high-quality open-source

00:25:53.219 --> 00:25:59.099
software that is accessible to anyone, anywhere, regardless of their economic means.

00:25:59.099 --> 00:26:02.699
In order to make sure that the business would be sustainable longer-term, we decided to

00:26:02.699 --> 00:26:07.619
build a software-only business that sells commercial versions of our open-source server

00:26:07.619 --> 00:26:10.020
products.

00:26:10.020 --> 00:26:15.739
These products help enterprises adopt R and open science tools in production environments.

00:26:15.739 --> 00:26:19.900
The differentiation between our open-source products and our commercial products lie in

00:26:19.900 --> 00:26:24.979
capabilities around security, authentication, monitoring, tuning, scaling, metrics, collaboration,

00:26:24.979 --> 00:26:25.979
sharing.

00:26:25.979 --> 00:26:29.579
You get a commercial license and premium support.

00:26:29.579 --> 00:26:39.780
Our hope is that we can sustain this virtuous cycle, which allows us to then invest in the

00:26:39.780 --> 00:26:43.260
areas of the greatest needs for the R community.

00:26:43.260 --> 00:26:47.339
So far, things have been going really well.

00:26:47.339 --> 00:26:51.979
The open-source packages make R more and more accessible, which in turn drives the adoption

00:26:51.979 --> 00:26:56.739
of R in enterprises, which hopefully creates more demand for our commercial products, which

00:26:56.739 --> 00:27:00.380
then allows us to fund even more open-source work.

00:27:00.380 --> 00:27:01.380
This is it.

00:27:01.380 --> 00:27:04.819
This is like it's really, really simple, right?

00:27:04.819 --> 00:27:09.380
Put it another way, our open-source products create value for everyone, and our commercial

00:27:09.380 --> 00:27:12.560
products help businesses leverage that value.

00:27:12.560 --> 00:27:17.060
We believe that this gives the open-source community benefits because you have talented,

00:27:17.060 --> 00:27:22.420
paid open-source developers creating a growing number of free, high-quality R packages that

00:27:22.420 --> 00:27:25.020
can be consistently maintained.

00:27:25.020 --> 00:27:29.060
Commercial customers benefit from a financially viable and sustainable ecosystem of these

00:27:29.060 --> 00:27:33.760
open-source tools and packages, along with products that meet their enterprise IT standards

00:27:33.760 --> 00:27:36.020
for deployment and production.

00:27:36.020 --> 00:27:41.540
A thriving ecosystem of education, training, and services can bring energy, new ideas,

00:27:41.540 --> 00:27:46.540
and talent to create and share data products at a fraction of the cost and hopefully improve

00:27:46.540 --> 00:27:50.819
our societies and our world.

00:27:50.819 --> 00:27:54.819
Thank you so much for your attention and for taking the time to attend the conference.

00:27:54.819 --> 00:27:58.819
We are very excited to have the opportunity to spend a few days together.

